rocess. It gives Git hosting/API/proxy capabilities.\nTo make `git-meta-lib` happy, the generator still has to materialize a real\nlocal Git repository/object database/ref namespace on disk, even if the remote\nit fetches from is Pierre/code.storage.\n\nPierre may still be useful in front of that local repository:\n\n- If code.storage can import or mirror the public GitHub repository an\n[TRUNCATED]\n- The repository cache is rebuildable from public metadata refs, so it is not\n- Railway volumes mount read/write persistent storage into a service\n  ([Railway volumes](https://docs.railway.com/volumes)).\n\nImplication: deploy the Agent Trail app as a long-lived container with a\npersistent volume. Do not use Vercel/serverless for generation.\n\n### Rust / Node Boundary\n\nNAPI is the cleanest Rust-to-Node bridge only if the Agent Trail app is a Node\nweb process. A Rust web app can avoid the bridge entirely.\n\nRelevant findings:\n\n- Node-API is ABI-stable across Node versions, which makes it the right native\n  addon foundation\n  ([Node-API docs](https://nodejs.org/api/n-api.html)).\n- `napi-rs` can build Rust native addons and emit platform-suffixed `.node`\n  artifacts such as `index.darwin-x64.node`\n  ([napi-rs CLI](https://napi-rs.github.io/napi-rs/cli/)).\n- A helper binary is operationally simpler than NAPI in some deployments because\n  it isolates crashes and avoids native addon bundling, but it still requires\n  binary packaging, filesystem access, `git`, and a cache.\n- WASM/WASI is a bad fit. Node's WASI support is still marked experimental, and\n  Rust's base WASI target does not support process spawning. Agent Trail wants\n  real Git repository behavior, so WASM adds friction without removing the hard\n  dependency.\n\nImplication: prefer a Rust web app that links the projection API directly. If\nthe app must run on Node, prefer a dedicated `but-agenttrail-napi` package and\nexternalize it from Next bundling.\n\n### Current Recommendation\n\nBuild this as one deployable Agent Trail app:\n\n- HTTP/API/page layer: URL replacement, GitHub PR lookup, public JSON contract,\n  status polling, snapshot route, and UI.\n- internal generation layer: local repository cache, metadata fetch, GitMeta\n  materialization, `but-agentlog` projection, locking, cleanup, and result\n  storage.\n\nKeep those layers separate in code, but do not split them across a network\nboundary for v1. The app should live in its own repo and deploy as one stateful\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-24T16:19:13.402Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}